Rating: 4
Tried this for the first time this week and the ribs came out great (yeah, it's cheatin' ribs, but it's a darn good recipe with tender moist ribs :-) I had no problems w/ the beer evaporating; the foil is supposed to cover the roasting pan *tightly* to prevent this and it does. Only problem I had was that I had to stack the ribs on top of each other. The ribs that were in the beer were more moist and tender than the ones stacked on top which weren't on the beer. No need to use baby back ribs either. I used regular pork ribs and they came out great. The sauce also has a slightly bitter aftertaste, but it's a very full bodied taste. I think it's from the expresso, so I might cut it back next time or add more sugar. I did replace half the water in the sauce recipe w/ bourbon to add more flavor to it. I used the Bulleye Hickory sauce as the base since America's Test Kitchen said it was the best sauce. I also used Guiness Extra Stout for the beer since that's less bitter than most dark beers.

